      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're pointing out the inherent bias in how these systems operate, which is a well-known issue. When judges rely on socioeconomic proxies like neighborhood or employment history, they are often unconsciously applying racial stereotypes. The principle of equal protection is supposed to prevent this, but in practice, these risk assessments often end up punishing poverty and race rather than just the crime itself. A judge trying to be fair would have to actively fight against these ingrained biases in the guidelines.",
